Lockington, Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Lockington, Yorkshire, England","Lockington, East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1245–Bef 1281":"1245–before 1281","1250–1312":"1250–1312","1278–1341":"1278–1341","1245–1281":"1245–1281","1259":"1259","1312":"1312","1245":"1245","1278":"1278","1341":"1341","1250":"1250","Bef 1281":"before 1281","1281":"1281","Lockington, Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Lockington, Yorkshire, England","Lockington, East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Daniel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Romanian, Jewish, Assyrian/Chaldean, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and African (mainly Nigeria and Tanzania); Breton (rarely <b>Le Daniel</b>); Hungarian (<b>Dániel</b>): from the Biblical personal name <i>Daniel</i>, Syriac (Assyrian/Chaldean) <i>Dānīʾēl</i>, Hungarian <i>Dániel</i> (from Hebrew <i>Daniyyel</i> ‘God is my judge’), borne by a major prophet in the Bible. The chief factor influencing the popularity of the personal name (and hence the frequency of the surname) was undoubtedly the dramatic story in the Book of Daniel recounting the prophet's steadfast adherence to his religious faith despite pressure and persecution from the Mesopotamian kings in whose court he served: Nebuchadnezzar, Belshazzar, and Darius. The name was also borne by a 2nd-century Christian martyr and by a 9th-century hermit, the legend of whose lives were popular among Christians during the Middle Ages. Among Orthodox Christians in Eastern Europe the name was also popular as being that of a 4th-century Persian martyr, who was venerated in the Orthodox Church. In France, this surname is most common in Brittany.","Irish (Tipperary and Waterford): shortened form of   McDaniel  , which is actually a variant of   McDonnell  , from the Gaelic form of Irish <i>Donal</i> (equivalent to Scottish <i>Donald</i>), erroneously associated with the Biblical personal name <i>Daniel</i>. See also   O'Donnell  .","Americanized or Germanized form of Slovenian <b>Danijel</b>: from the Biblical personal name <i>Danijel</i> ‘Daniel’ (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Daane","meanings":["Dutch: from a short form of the personal name   Daniel  . Compare   Dane  ."]},{"name":"Dan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Ha To, Hieu, Lam, Chinh, Dung, Dung Anh, Long, Ly, Mai, Minh, Nga, Nguyen Van.  Romanian Corneliu, Silviu, Constantin, Dumitru, Ilie, Rodica, Stelian, Vasile.","Romanian; Hungarian (mainly <b>Dán</b>): from a short form of the Biblical personal name   Daniel   (Hungarian <i>Dániel</i>).","Romanian: from a short form of the Slavic personal names   Bogdan   and   Prodan  ."]},{"name":"Dacko","meanings":["Polish: from a pet form of an Old Polish compound personal names beginning with <i>Da-</i> (for example, <i>Dalebor</i>), or of the Biblical names   Daniel   or <i>Dawid</i> (Polish form of   David  ).","Americanized form of Ukrainian <b>Datsko</b>: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Danylo</i>, Ukrainian equivalent of   Daniel  ."]},{"name":"McDaniel","meanings":["Irish: altered form of   McDonnell  , itself an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Domhnaill</b> ‘son of Donal’, from association of the Gaelic patronymic with the Biblical personal name   Daniel  ."]},{"name":"Danel","meanings":["French and Polish: from a variant of the personal name   Daniel  ."]},{"name":"Danca","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Nicola, Salvatore.","Portuguese (<b>Dança</b>): perhaps a nickname from <i>dança</i> ‘dance’.","Italian (<b>D'Anca</b>): probably a nickname from the vocabulary word <i>anca</i> ‘hip, haunch’."]},{"name":"Dani","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Narendra, Saryu, Shashi, Bachu, Chandu, Devyani, Dilip, Dinesh, Hasit, Kaushik, Kirit, Manisha.","Italian, Romanian, and German; Slovak (also <b>Dáni</b>): from a short form of the personal name   Daniel   (Italian <i>Daniele</i>).","Albanian: from <i>Dan</i> (definite form <i>Dani</i>), a short form of the Muslim personal name   Ramadan  ."]},{"name":"Dagneau","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French: variant, written under the influence of the word <i>agneau</i> ‘lamb’, of <b>Daniau</b>, which is from the personal name <i>Daniau</i>, a variant of   Daniel  . Compare   Daignault  ,   Daigneau  ,   Daigneault  , and   Danyow  .","History: The progenitor of the (majority of the) American Dagneaus was Michel Dagneau, <i>sieur</i> de Douville from Deux-Jumeaux in Calvados, France, who married Marie Lamy in Sorel, QC, in 1688. His descendants mostly bear altered forms of the surname, mentioned above."]},{"name":"Dangel","meanings":["German: from a vernacular form of the personal name   Daniel  . This surname is also found in France (Alsace)."]},{"name":"Danek","meanings":["Czech (<b>Daněk</b>), Slovak, and Polish: from a pet form of   Daniel   or of any of the Slavic compound personal names formed with the element <i>dan</i> ‘given’ (see   Dana  ).","Czech (<b>Daněk</b>): nickname from <i>daněk</i> ‘fallow deer’."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: The Scripture name, in Hebrew, Adham, signifying 'man;' literally earthy, red earth; Rudolph, however, says the name in Ethiopic means ' to be fair, beautiful.' Hence the nurse-name Addy, little Adam."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":14,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Adam Daniel was born in 1245, in Lockington, Yorkshire, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Agnes. He died before 1281."},